cs|1|ht|b|fp|1|cp||at|^a^*b^-{      1-OF-A-MAJOR OPPOSITE A PASSED HAND      ^*n|fp||
at|^^|fp|1|cp||at|^a^*b  Larry Cohen - Date of publish: 02/27/2014 - Level: Intermediate  }^*n|fp||
at|^^|fp|1|cp||at|^a^*b^-^*n|fp||
at|^b@2|at|^^|cp|5|at|^b^*bLarry Cohen: ^*n|
cp||at|Last month, we discussed 1-of-a-Major Openings. Now we delve into the follow-ups by a Passed Hand.|
ht|h|cp||at|^bLet's examine the following auctions:|
cs|1|ht|i|cs|1|cp||at|^b{}|
at|{|ia|-pp1hp?|at|}|cs|1|ht|i|cs|1|cp||at|^m{}|
at|{|ia|ppp1hp?|at|}|cs|1|ht|n|cs|1|cp||at|^b{}|
at|{|ia|-pp1sp?|at|}|cs|1|ht|n|cs|1|cp||at|^b{}|
at|{|ia|ppp1sp?|at|}|at|^b@2|ht|t|cp||at|^bIn each case, the 3rd or 4th seat opening was 1-of-a-major. For the responder, what should change? Last month, when responder was an UPH ("unpassed hand") there were all sorts of strong possibilities (such as a Jacoby 2NT raise, Splinter bids, 2/1 Game-force responses). Now, the responder has at most 11, maybe 12 points. Everything is different. |
cp||at|^*bEverything, that is, except a single raise. 1@h-2@h and 1@s-2@s should retain the same meaning as by an UPH.^*n|
